title: Experimental measurements and nuclear model calculations on the excitation functions of nat-Ce(3He,xn) and 141Pr(p,xn) reactions with special reference to production of the therapeutic radionuclide 140Nd.

x4freetext: Experimental measurements and nuclear model
calculations on the excitation functions of
nat-Ce(3He,xn) and 141Pr(p,xn) reactions with special
reference to production of the therapeutic radionuclide
The compact cyclotron CV-28. Protons of
energies 12, 16 and 20 MeV and 3-He-particles of
energies 25 and 36 MeV.
The injector of "COSY".  Protons of
energy 45 MeV.
Ce-O(2) and Pr(2)O(3) of natural isotopic composition
and high chemical purity-99.999% were used to prepare
thin samples by sedimentation. A 25 um thick Cu-foil,
99.9% pure, with a diameter of 13-mm served as the
backing of the sample. After evaporation of the acetone
the sample was taken out, the sample was covered and
wrapped up at the margin by a thin Al-foil, 10 um
thickness, 16-mm diameter, 99.9% pure.
The exciton model code `ALICE-IPPE`.
The integral yield of each investigated radio-
nuclide via a nuclear reaction was calculated.
Total uncertainty includes:
The uncertainty in number of target
nuclei
The uncertainty in target uniformity
The uncertainty in efficiency of the
detector
The uncertainty in peak area is 2-8%.
The uncertainty in cross section of
monitor reaction is 8-10%.
The uncertainty in decay data is 1%.
Tbls 3,4 from Radiochim. Acta 93(2005)553
Last checking has been done.

to be measured and the cross section were added.  The
uncertainty for this cross section is therefore higher
than for the other reactions.  Furthermore, the ground
state had to be corrected for the internal transition
11.8% of the isomeric state to the ground state.

x4freetext: The Ce-139 formation cross section is the cumulative
cross section of the processes:
1.  Nat-Ce(He3,X)Nd-139.
2.  Nat-Ce(He3,X)Pr-140.
3.  Nat-Ce(He3,X)Ce-139.
